04629nam a22005775i 9780292769151DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211985txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927691517 a10.7560/7272812doi  a(DE-B1597)588349  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0260002bisacsh1 aMiller, Ylana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGovernment and Society in Rural Palestine, 1920-1948 /cYlana Miller. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1985  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE Community and the State -- t1. The Palestine Mandate, 1918-1948: A Political Overview -- t2. Nationalism and Village Society -- tPART TWO Government and Society, 1920-1936 -- t3. The Formation of a Government -- t4. The Formation of a Public Service Links to the Villages -- t5. Village Administration -- t6. Rural Education -- tPART THREE Government and Society, 1936-1948 -- t7. The Arab Revolt -- t8. Government and Society: Interdependence during the War Years -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1947, Arabs made up two-thirds of the population of Palestine, and they owned most of its cultivable land. Why then, did they "lose" their homes and land to a relatively small Jewish community just emerging from the shocks of World War II? Did the Palestinians "lose" their homeland because they were backward, primitive, and reactionary? Or was Israel the product of persistent victimization of Palestinian Arabs by an imperialist power which supported Zionist colonization? Did the Palestinians sell each other out? Or were they helpless sufferers in the face of a sophisticated enemy with endless resources? Too often discussions of Palestine are couched in such rhetorical language, based on the assumption that either Jews or Arabs are morally to blame for historical realities. This study seeks to go beyond attributions of responsibility to investigate the concrete conditions which determined and limited Palestinian Arab actions between 1920 and 1948. It was during that period, while Great Britain governed the area under a League of Nations mandate, that Palestine both emerged and disappeared as a modern political entity. Many studies of Palestinian Arab nationalism have looked to Zionism as the primary agent of change in the region. Miller assumes the impact of Jewish settlement but goes beyond these earlier studies to explore the way in which policies of the Palestine government affected the daily lives of villagers—the majority of the population—and their understanding of the changes occurring around them. In this way, what emerges is a detailed analysis of the influence, for good or ill, that government policy had on village community life. Based largely on archival sources never before used, this work allows the reader to gain a deeper appreciation of the internal life of the rural community, which had previously received relatively little attention. Understanding the experiences of Palestinians before 1948 helps us to comprehend immeasurably better the continuity of movements for Palestinian statehood as well as the continuing tensions and problems on the West Bank today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72728140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292769151423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292769151/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGr